  "prompt": "Why does Peter Thiel hate Gawker?",
  "response": "Peter Thiel, a billionaire entrepreneur and co-founder of PayPal, has been a vocal critic of Gawker Media, a now-defunct online media company. Thiel's animosity towards Gawker stems from a 2007 article published by the now-shuttered website Gawker.com, which outed him as gay without his consent. At the time, Thiel had not publicly disclosed his sexual orientation, and the article was seen as a significant invasion of his privacy.\n\nThiel saw the outing as a violation of journalistic ethics and personal boundaries. In response, he secretly funded a series of lawsuits against Gawker, including one brought by professional wrestler Hulk Hogan (real name Terry Bollea). Hogan sued Gawker for posting a sex tape involving him without his consent. Thiel provided financial backing for Hogan's legal team, which ultimately won a $140 million judgment against Gawker in 2016. This legal victory forced Gawker Media into bankruptcy, and the company was subsequently sold off in parts.\n\nThiel has stated that his actions were motivated by a desire to hold Gawker accountable for what he viewed as its reckless and harmful journalism. He has argued that the media company had a history of crossing ethical lines and causing harm to individuals' lives. Thiel's actions have been both praised and criticized; some see them as a form of vigilante justice against a publication that often pushed the boundaries of acceptable behavior, while others view them as a dangerous precedent that could lead to wealthy individuals using their resources to silence the press.\n\nIn summary, Peter Thiel's hatred for Gawker is primarily rooted in the company's decision to out him publicly, which he viewed as a profound breach of privacy and journalistic responsibility. His subsequent financial support of lawsuits against Gawker was aimed at holding the company accountable for its actions.",
